<paragraph id="A711A066FF96D06AFEBCF9C3FEA08E4E" blockId="1.[264,1324,1649,1875]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1323,284,353]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName id="60AEDBE5FF96D069FEBCF9C3FDD0899A" box="[264,512,1649,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Trichomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fairchildi">
<emphasis id="95DA7C74FF96D069FEBCF9C3FDD0899A" box="[264,512,1649,1674]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Trichomyia fairchildi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described based only on wing characteristics (
<figureCitation id="3F95BCE3FF96D069FBE7F9C3FB47899B" box="[1107,1175,1649,1675]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,368,830,854]" captionTargetBox="[380,1204,470,793]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[373,1214,452,805]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Wing of Trichomyia fairchildi Vargas and Díaz­Nájera." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/157715/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Fig. 
<number id="1166B241FF96D069FB3EF9C3FB47899B" box="[1162,1175,1649,1675]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
), the unique structure preserved in a microscope slide by Dr. Alphonse Dampf in 
<number id="1166B241FF96D069FBFBF92BFB5D89A3" box="[1103,1165,1689,1715]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1947.0">1947</number>
. Because the wing characteristics are not useful alone for species recognition, it is necessary to consider it as 
<emphasis id="95DA7C74FF96D069FEF4F95BFDCC8812" box="[320,540,1769,1794]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">species inquirenda</emphasis>
. Nevertheless, it is important to mention that this specimen shares wing characteristics with 
<taxonomicName id="60AEDBE5FF96D069FD83F8A3FC7C883B" authority="Curtis, 1839" authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1839" box="[567,940,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Trichomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="urbica">
<emphasis id="95DA7C74FF96D069FD83F8A3FCC1883A" box="[567,785,1809,1834]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Trichomyia urbica</emphasis>
Curtis, 
<number id="1166B241FF96D069FCC5F8A3FC7C883B" box="[881,940,1809,1835]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1839.0">1839</number>
</taxonomicName>
(as figured by Vargas and Díaz­ Nájera 
<number id="1166B241FF96D069FEEBF88BFE4C8843" box="[351,412,1849,1875]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1953.0">1953</number>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="C33FDD97FF96D069FE6AF88BFD548843" author="Satchell" box="[478,644,1849,1875]" pageId="1" pageNumber="13" refString="Satchell, G. H. (1956) On the genus Trichomyia Haliday (Diptera: Psychodidae), with descriptions of four new species. The Proceedings of the Royal Entomological Society of London (B), 25, 147 - 156." type="journal article" year="1956">
Satchell 
<number id="1166B241FF96D069FDF2F88BFD548843" box="[582,644,1849,1875]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1956.0">1956</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), such as the broadly rounded wing apex, the radial fork apicad of the wing center, vein r­m present, and the median fork approximately at the level of CuA 
<number id="1166B241FF95D06AFEEBFEE2FEB98E71" box="[351,361,336,353]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2.0">2</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
